WEBVTT

00:00.120 --> 00:03.460
We are gonna talk about linting.

00:03.460 --> 00:05.520
Who is pumped about linting?

00:05.520 --> 00:06.360
Get out.

00:06.360 --> 00:07.200
No, I'm just kidding.

00:07.200 --> 00:10.100
I'm just kidding.

00:11.760 --> 00:13.160
I got mixed feelings about linting.

00:13.160 --> 00:15.760
You know, I've gone all over the map from on linting.

00:17.160 --> 00:19.160
I used to be, and if you watch like,

00:19.160 --> 00:21.880
completed intro to React V2,

00:21.880 --> 00:23.840
like there comes in this like,

00:23.840 --> 00:26.200
different Brian Holt character that's just like,

00:26.200 --> 00:28.640
we're gonna lint the hell out of this project.

00:28.640 --> 00:30.200
It's gonna look like one person wrote it.

00:30.200 --> 00:32.000
And I was very much on that train of like,

00:32.000 --> 00:34.160
let's let the tools control you.

00:35.360 --> 00:38.560
And I've come all the way back the other way.

00:38.560 --> 00:40.880
And like, if you like watch like React V7,

00:40.880 --> 00:42.400
you get like this like hippie Brian,

00:42.400 --> 00:44.880
it's like free love and no linting, right?

00:44.880 --> 00:46.280
Where I'm just like,

00:46.280 --> 00:48.600
write whatever code you feel like, dude, right?

00:48.600 --> 00:53.520
And now I've come back more to like,

00:53.520 --> 00:57.400
help me catch very common and very easy to miss bugs

00:57.400 --> 01:00.240
and otherwise leave me the hell alone.

01:00.240 --> 01:01.200
This actually just kind of applies

01:01.200 --> 01:04.960
to my general thought process on building dev tools

01:04.960 --> 01:08.240
of your developer has something in mind

01:08.240 --> 01:10.360
that they wanna express in the code

01:10.360 --> 01:14.640
and don't interrupt them unless they're actually going to,

01:14.640 --> 01:16.320
unless you're helping them, right?

01:17.580 --> 01:22.360
Like just getting someone to write code in a certain format

01:22.360 --> 01:24.880
because you feel like it is adding more and more friction

01:24.880 --> 01:27.480
and it's more distance between someone expressing

01:27.480 --> 01:28.640
their idea and code.

01:29.760 --> 01:31.960
And so that's why I'm much more careful these days

01:31.960 --> 01:35.960
to be very light on the linting side.

01:35.960 --> 01:40.240
And just like, if it's not important, don't do it, right?

01:41.120 --> 01:41.960
Okay.

01:43.720 --> 01:47.680
So we're gonna do prettier and people frequently ask me like,

01:47.680 --> 01:50.720
what's the difference between linting and,

01:50.720 --> 01:52.480
or ES lint and prettier?

01:53.480 --> 01:56.040
ES lint is linting, obviously.

01:56.040 --> 02:01.040
Linting is much more like semantics and syntax

02:02.280 --> 02:05.480
and content focused where you're saying things like,

02:07.040 --> 02:09.200
you have to alphabetize all of your imports,

02:09.200 --> 02:11.680
which is like one of my very least favorite rules

02:11.680 --> 02:15.280
that you can enforce in ES lint.

02:15.280 --> 02:16.400
But it's things like that.

02:16.400 --> 02:18.720
It's things where you're enforcing an opinion on someone.

02:18.720 --> 02:21.520
Like it could be totally valid code, but you're saying,

02:21.520 --> 02:23.400
I don't want you to do this.

02:23.400 --> 02:24.960
One of the ones that I do find useful

02:24.960 --> 02:27.720
is don't use any globals, right?

02:27.720 --> 02:30.200
Because usually that means that like you misspelled

02:30.200 --> 02:31.920
something so it's gonna reach for a global

02:31.920 --> 02:35.240
as opposed to finding the one that you actually intended

02:35.240 --> 02:36.360
to name it, right?

02:36.360 --> 02:37.760
Prettier is just formatting.

02:37.760 --> 02:40.600
It's just white space and new lines.

02:40.600 --> 02:42.600
It does not enforce anything about the code.

02:42.600 --> 02:44.320
It's just making sure that all of the white space

02:44.320 --> 02:46.320
ends up in the right place.

02:46.320 --> 02:48.320
That's all that prettier does.

02:48.320 --> 02:50.520
There's some overlap that you can basically have ES lint

02:50.520 --> 02:52.680
do some of what prettier does.

02:52.680 --> 02:54.280
But if we're using both tools,

02:54.280 --> 02:56.160
prettier is much better at formatting.

02:56.160 --> 02:57.680
Leave the formatting to prettier.

02:57.680 --> 03:01.480
Just have lint for all of the linting rules.

03:01.480 --> 03:02.800
Yeah, Mark.

